{"TopicId":188514,"ForumId":44,"TopicTitle":"Unknown Facts About Exoplanets","CreatedByName":"caballerodiez","CreatedById":190290,"CreatedDateTime":"2019-09-27T21:00:54Z","PageNum":1,"Articles":[{"CreatedByName":"caballerodiez","CreatedById":190290,"CreatedDateTime":"2019-09-27T21:00:55Z","Content":"\n\u003Cp style=\u0022color:#222222;font-size:15px;\u0022\u003E\nHi!\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cp style=\u0022color:#222222;font-size:15px;\u0022\u003E\nIf you are interested in exoplanets, you might want to know these little known facts about exoplanets.\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cp style=\u0022color:#222222;font-size:15px;\u0022\u003E\nSource:\u00A0\u003Ca href=\u0022https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=In2DjQQ1oyc\u0022 rel=\u0022external nofollow\u0022\u003Ehttps://www.youtube.com/watch?v=In2DjQQ1oyc\u003C/a\u003E\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Col style=\u0022color:#222222;font-size:15px;padding:0px 40px;\u0022\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\nIn our stellar neighborhood there might be around 130 potentially (p.) habitable exoplanets, 10 of them being Earth-like.\n\u003C/li\u003E\n\u003Cli\u003E\nThe closest p. Earth-like planet is called Tau Ceti e, and it is located only 12 light years away from us.\n\u003C/li\u003E\n\u003Cli\u003E\nSo far, we have sent a targeted radio message to 2 p. habitable exoplanets, Tau Ceti e and Luyten b. Any reply would be received as of 2037 and 2041, respectively.\n\u003C/li\u003E\n\u003Cli\u003E\nAmateur astronomers have discovered 2 p. habitable exoplanets: LHS-1140 b and K2-288 B b.\n\u003C/li\u003E\n\u003Cli\u003E\nIt is possible to detect exoplanets by using a tele-photo lens with an aperture of less than 50 mm.\n\u003C/li\u003E\n\u003C/ol\u003E\u003Cp style=\u0022color:#222222;font-size:15px;\u0022\u003E\nHope you learnt something knew!\n\u003C/p\u003E\n"},{"CreatedByName":"Geonovast","CreatedById":179753,"CreatedDateTime":"2019-09-27T21:10:11Z","Content":"\n\u003Cp\u003E\nMoving to Science \u0026amp; Spaceflight.\n\u003C/p\u003E\n"},{"CreatedByName":"DDE","CreatedById":146349,"CreatedDateTime":"2019-09-27T21:41:23Z","Content":"\n\u003Cblockquote class=\u0022ipsQuote\u0022 data-ipsquote=\u0022\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentapp=\u0022forums\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentclass=\u0022forums_Topic\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentcommentid=\u00223678301\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentid=\u0022188514\u0022 data-ipsquote-contenttype=\u0022forums\u0022 data-ipsquote-timestamp=\u00221569618055\u0022 data-ipsquote-userid=\u0022190290\u0022 data-ipsquote-username=\u0022caballerodiez\u0022\u003E\n\u003Cdiv class=\u0022ipsQuote_citation\u0022\u003E\n38 minutes ago, caballerodiez said:\n\u003C/div\u003E\n\u003Cdiv class=\u0022ipsQuote_contents\u0022\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\nEarth-like\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003C/div\u003E\n\u003C/blockquote\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\n*groan*\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\nThey\u0027re super-Earths, and the more we look at them, the less they look like Earth.\n\u003C/p\u003E\n"},{"CreatedByName":"Shpaget","CreatedById":45577,"CreatedDateTime":"2019-09-28T04:48:06Z","Content":"\n\u003Cblockquote class=\u0022ipsQuote\u0022 data-ipsquote=\u0022\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentapp=\u0022forums\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentclass=\u0022forums_Topic\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentcommentid=\u00223678301\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentid=\u0022188514\u0022 data-ipsquote-contenttype=\u0022forums\u0022 data-ipsquote-timestamp=\u00221569618055\u0022 data-ipsquote-userid=\u0022190290\u0022 data-ipsquote-username=\u0022caballerodiez\u0022\u003E\n\u003Cdiv class=\u0022ipsQuote_citation\u0022\u003E\n7 hours ago, caballerodiez said:\n\u003C/div\u003E\n\u003Cdiv class=\u0022ipsQuote_contents\u0022\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\nIt is possible to detect exoplanets by using a tele-photo lens with an aperture of less than 50 mm.\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003C/div\u003E\n\u003C/blockquote\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\nThis does not compute.\n\u003C/p\u003E\n"},{"CreatedByName":"cubinator","CreatedById":150330,"CreatedDateTime":"2019-09-28T04:55:14Z","Content":"\n\u003Cblockquote class=\u0022ipsQuote\u0022 data-ipsquote=\u0022\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentapp=\u0022forums\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentclass=\u0022forums_Topic\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentcommentid=\u00223678449\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentid=\u0022188514\u0022 data-ipsquote-contenttype=\u0022forums\u0022 data-ipsquote-timestamp=\u00221569646086\u0022 data-ipsquote-userid=\u002245577\u0022 data-ipsquote-username=\u0022Shpaget\u0022\u003E\n\u003Cdiv class=\u0022ipsQuote_citation\u0022\u003E\n6 minutes ago, Shpaget said:\n\u003C/div\u003E\n\u003Cdiv class=\u0022ipsQuote_contents\u0022\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\nThis does not compute.\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003C/div\u003E\n\u003C/blockquote\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\nMaybe with spectroscopy on transiting planets only?\n\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cblockquote class=\u0022ipsQuote\u0022 data-ipsquote=\u0022\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentapp=\u0022forums\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentclass=\u0022forums_Topic\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentcommentid=\u00223678319\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentid=\u0022188514\u0022 data-ipsquote-contenttype=\u0022forums\u0022 data-ipsquote-timestamp=\u00221569620483\u0022 data-ipsquote-userid=\u0022146349\u0022 data-ipsquote-username=\u0022DDE\u0022\u003E\n\u003Cdiv class=\u0022ipsQuote_citation\u0022\u003E\n7 hours ago, DDE said:\n\u003C/div\u003E\n\u003Cdiv class=\u0022ipsQuote_contents\u0022\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\n*groan*\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\nThey\u0027re super-Earths, and the more we look at them, the less they look like Earth.\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003C/div\u003E\n\u003C/blockquote\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\nAt least we have two about the same size as Earth in Teegarden\u0027s system.\n\u003C/p\u003E\n"},{"CreatedByName":"Shpaget","CreatedById":45577,"CreatedDateTime":"2019-09-28T08:49:51Z","Content":"\n\u003Cp\u003E\nHmm, haven\u0027t thought of that, but 50 mm won\u0027t get you much resolution, even with diffraction limited optics.\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\nAnyway, the \u0022less than 50 mm \u0022 is weird way to put it, since 2 mm aperture is less than 50, and would be useless for the purpose.\n\u003C/p\u003E\n"},{"CreatedByName":"kerbiloid","CreatedById":129408,"CreatedDateTime":"2019-09-28T13:42:11Z","Content":"\n\u003Cp\u003E\nWhat they call Earth-like, is probably either a Superearth as said above, or a teenager Venus.\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cspan class=\u0022ipsType_reset ipsType_medium ipsType_light\u0022 data-excludequote=\u0022\u0022\u003E\n\u003Cstrong\u003EEdited \u003Ctime datetime=\u00222019-09-28T13:42:48Z\u0022 title=\u002209/28/2019 01:42  PM\u0022 data-short=\u00224 yr\u0022\u003ESeptember 28, 2019\u003C/time\u003E by kerbiloid\u003C/strong\u003E\n\u003C/span\u003E\n"},{"CreatedByName":"UmbralRaptor","CreatedById":2767,"CreatedDateTime":"2019-09-28T15:05:00Z","Content":"\n\u003Cp\u003E\nNote that for our purposes, Venus and Mars are \u0022Earthlike\u0022, so be careful not to take \u0022habitable\u0022 too literally.\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cblockquote class=\u0022ipsQuote\u0022 data-ipsquote=\u0022\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentapp=\u0022forums\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentclass=\u0022forums_Topic\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentcommentid=\u00223678449\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentid=\u0022188514\u0022 data-ipsquote-contenttype=\u0022forums\u0022 data-ipsquote-timestamp=\u00221569646086\u0022 data-ipsquote-userid=\u002245577\u0022 data-ipsquote-username=\u0022Shpaget\u0022\u003E\n\u003Cdiv class=\u0022ipsQuote_citation\u0022\u003E\n10 hours ago, Shpaget said:\n\u003C/div\u003E\n\u003Cdiv class=\u0022ipsQuote_contents\u0022\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\nThis does not compute.\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003C/div\u003E\n\u003C/blockquote\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\n\u003Ca href=\u0022https://keltsurvey.org/telescopes\u0022 rel=\u0022external nofollow\u0022\u003EYou might think so, but it totally works for KELT.\u003C/a\u003E \u003Ca href=\u0022https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wide_Angle_Search_for_Planets\u0022 rel=\u0022external nofollow\u0022\u003EWASP\u003C/a\u003E and \u003Ca href=\u0022https://heasarc.gsfc.nasa.gov/docs/tess/the-tess-space-telescope.html\u0022 rel=\u0022external nofollow\u0022\u003ETESS\u003C/a\u003E aren\u0027t *that* much bigger, also.\n\u003C/p\u003E\n"},{"CreatedByName":"caballerodiez","CreatedById":190290,"CreatedDateTime":"2019-09-28T17:18:29Z","Content":"\n\u003Cblockquote class=\u0022ipsQuote\u0022 data-ipsquote=\u0022\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentapp=\u0022forums\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentclass=\u0022forums_Topic\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentcommentid=\u00223678606\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentid=\u0022188514\u0022 data-ipsquote-contenttype=\u0022forums\u0022 data-ipsquote-timestamp=\u00221569683100\u0022 data-ipsquote-userid=\u00222767\u0022 data-ipsquote-username=\u0022UmbralRaptor\u0022\u003E\n\u003Cdiv class=\u0022ipsQuote_citation\u0022\u003E\n2 hours ago, UmbralRaptor said:\n\u003C/div\u003E\n\u003Cdiv class=\u0022ipsQuote_contents\u0022\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\nNote that for our purposes, Venus and Mars are \u0022Earthlike\u0022, so be careful not to take \u0022habitable\u0022 too literally.\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\n\u003Ca href=\u0022https://keltsurvey.org/telescopes\u0022 rel=\u0022external nofollow\u0022\u003EYou might think so, but it totally works for KELT.\u003C/a\u003E \u003Ca href=\u0022https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wide_Angle_Search_for_Planets\u0022 rel=\u0022external nofollow\u0022\u003EWASP\u003C/a\u003E and \u003Ca href=\u0022https://heasarc.gsfc.nasa.gov/docs/tess/the-tess-space-telescope.html\u0022 rel=\u0022external nofollow\u0022\u003ETESS\u003C/a\u003E aren\u0027t *that* much bigger, also.\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003C/div\u003E\n\u003C/blockquote\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\nTrue.\u00A0 TESS lenses have an aperture of just 100mm (4 inches).\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cspan class=\u0022ipsType_reset ipsType_medium ipsType_light\u0022 data-excludequote=\u0022\u0022\u003E\n\u003Cstrong\u003EEdited \u003Ctime datetime=\u00222019-09-28T17:25:58Z\u0022 title=\u002209/28/2019 05:25  PM\u0022 data-short=\u00224 yr\u0022\u003ESeptember 28, 2019\u003C/time\u003E by caballerodiez\u003C/strong\u003E\n\u003C/span\u003E\n"},{"CreatedByName":"kerbiloid","CreatedById":129408,"CreatedDateTime":"2019-09-29T04:48:47Z","Content":"\n\u003Cp\u003E\nSo, we should just call them \u0022Venus-like\u0022 planets, as probably only rarely one of the Venuses mutate into the Earth.\n\u003C/p\u003E\n"},{"CreatedByName":"DDE","CreatedById":146349,"CreatedDateTime":"2019-09-29T14:25:21Z","Content":"\n\u003Cblockquote class=\u0022ipsQuote\u0022 data-ipsquote=\u0022\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentapp=\u0022forums\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentclass=\u0022forums_Topic\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentcommentid=\u00223678878\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentid=\u0022188514\u0022 data-ipsquote-contenttype=\u0022forums\u0022 data-ipsquote-timestamp=\u00221569732527\u0022 data-ipsquote-userid=\u0022129408\u0022 data-ipsquote-username=\u0022kerbiloid\u0022\u003E\n\u003Cdiv class=\u0022ipsQuote_citation\u0022\u003E\n9 hours ago, kerbiloid said:\n\u003C/div\u003E\n\u003Cdiv class=\u0022ipsQuote_contents\u0022\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\nSo, we should just call them \u0022Venus-like\u0022 planets, as probably only rarely one of the Venuses mutate into the Earth.\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003C/div\u003E\n\u003C/blockquote\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\nMy - likely obsolete - understanding is that the \u003Ci\u003Ereal\u003C/i\u003E Goldilocks allows carbon sequestering into limestone, while sufficiency size and an active dynamo prevent all-around atmospheric loss.\n\u003C/p\u003E\n"},{"CreatedByName":"kerbiloid","CreatedById":129408,"CreatedDateTime":"2019-09-29T14:28:48Z","Content":"\n\u003Cblockquote class=\u0022ipsQuote\u0022 data-ipsquote=\u0022\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentapp=\u0022forums\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentclass=\u0022forums_Topic\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentcommentid=\u00223679022\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentid=\u0022188514\u0022 data-ipsquote-contenttype=\u0022forums\u0022 data-ipsquote-timestamp=\u00221569767121\u0022 data-ipsquote-userid=\u0022146349\u0022 data-ipsquote-username=\u0022DDE\u0022\u003E\n\u003Cdiv class=\u0022ipsQuote_citation\u0022\u003E\n5 minutes ago, DDE said:\n\u003C/div\u003E\n\u003Cdiv class=\u0022ipsQuote_contents\u0022\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\nactive dynamo\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003C/div\u003E\n\u003C/blockquote\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\nFrom where without a starter?\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\nHow many rocky bodies with dynamo do we know?\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cspan class=\u0022ipsType_reset ipsType_medium ipsType_light\u0022 data-excludequote=\u0022\u0022\u003E\n\u003Cstrong\u003EEdited \u003Ctime datetime=\u00222019-09-29T14:31:17Z\u0022 title=\u002209/29/2019 02:31  PM\u0022 data-short=\u00224 yr\u0022\u003ESeptember 29, 2019\u003C/time\u003E by kerbiloid\u003C/strong\u003E\n\u003C/span\u003E\n"},{"CreatedByName":"LaydeeDem","CreatedById":5984,"CreatedDateTime":"2019-10-01T15:55:42Z","Content":"\n\u003Cblockquote class=\u0022ipsQuote\u0022 data-ipsquote=\u0022\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentapp=\u0022forums\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentclass=\u0022forums_Topic\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentcommentid=\u00223678512\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentid=\u0022188514\u0022 data-ipsquote-contenttype=\u0022forums\u0022 data-ipsquote-timestamp=\u00221569660591\u0022 data-ipsquote-userid=\u002245577\u0022 data-ipsquote-username=\u0022Shpaget\u0022\u003E\n\u003Cdiv class=\u0022ipsQuote_citation\u0022\u003E\nOn 9/28/2019 at 2:49 AM, Shpaget said:\n\u003C/div\u003E\n\u003Cdiv class=\u0022ipsQuote_contents\u0022\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\nHmm, haven\u0027t thought of that, but 50 mm won\u0027t get you much resolution, even with diffraction limited optics.\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\nAnyway, the \u0022less than 50 mm \u0022 is weird way to put it, since 2 mm aperture is less than 50, and would be useless for the purpose.\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003C/div\u003E\n\u003C/blockquote\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\nvery few exoplanets are found through direct imaging. producing a lightcurve doesn\u0027t necessarily require a lot of aperture\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cspan class=\u0022ipsType_reset ipsType_medium ipsType_light\u0022 data-excludequote=\u0022\u0022\u003E\n\u003Cstrong\u003EEdited \u003Ctime datetime=\u00222019-10-01T15:55:49Z\u0022 title=\u002210/01/2019 03:55  PM\u0022 data-short=\u00224 yr\u0022\u003EOctober 1, 2019\u003C/time\u003E by LaydeeDem\u003C/strong\u003E\n\u003C/span\u003E\n"}]}